A. Insurance Business as Corporate Agent without risk Participation
A.1 Eligibility Conditions
15. An RCB shall be permitted to undertake insurance business as corporate agent without risk participation, subject to it fulfilling the following terms and conditions:
(1) An RCB shall be a Scheduled or licensed State Co-operative Bank (SCB) or a licensed District Central Co-operative Bank (DCCB);
(2) An RCB shall have a minimum positive net worth [real or exchangeable value of paid-up capital and reserves as defined in Section 11 of the Banking Regulation Act, 1949(AACS)] of ₹50 crore as per the latest NABARD Inspection Report;
(3) An RCB shall have earned net profit for the last three years and shall not have any accumulated losses;
(4) The Gross NPA of the RCB shall not exceed 10 percent;
(5) An RCB shall not have violated prudential norms including individual and group exposure norms;
(6) An RCB shall have complied with the guidelines on loans and advances to directors, their relatives and associated firms;
(7) Premium collection accounts shall not be opened with the RCB and premium collected shall be directly paid to the insurance companies;
(8) An RCB shall adhere to IRDAI regulations prescribed for corporate agents;
(9) An RCB shall submit an undertaking to the effect that banking business will not in any way get contaminated/affected on account of acting as agent of insurance companies; and
(10) An RCB shall not adopt any restrictive practice of compelling customers to opt for a specific insurance company, particularly in respect of assets financed by the RCB. Customers shall be free to exercise their own choice of insurer.

